The urban upper-middle class has pretty much the same type of global lifestyle all over the world. But when you want to reach the middle-class, then you have to go into Indian culture. That is when you need to come up with Indian symbols. Indian creatives are very good at that. See for example all the ads that use the character of the tapuri. The tapuri is a man from the street, a kind of Romeo from the neighborhood, he adds comedy to situations but he also adds an Indian feel, a typical Indian character.
Here, the archetype of the tapuri evokes some of the most successful advertising campaigns done for Indian brands, conceived at the advertising agency Ogilvy and Mather India for such brands as Asian Paints and Fevicol (see Figure 1
). The head of O&M, Piyush Pandey, a Rajasthani with a distinctive handlebar moustache, has made a career out of being able to write appealing scripts in Hindi, helping develop a new wave of advertisements that try to expand the appeal of brands by speaking a resolutely Indian language of references and characters. The emergence of creatives like Piyush Pandey, his brother Prasoon Pandey or R. Balakrishnan (CEO of ad agency Lowe Lintas and a Hindi film director) has inaugurated a new form of cultural capital within Indian advertising for those who can devise vernacular ads, scripts, and characters.
